#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:11
msgid ""
"**Users and System Administrators**: For those dealing with real-world "
"Ethernet issues, this guide provides a practical, step-by-step "
"troubleshooting flow to help identify and resolve common problems in Twisted "
"Pair Ethernet at OSI Layer 1. If you're facing unstable links, speed drops, "
"or mysterious network issues, jump right into the step-by-step guide and "
"follow it through to find your solution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:18
msgid ""
"**Kernel Developers**: For developers working with network drivers and PHY "
"support, this documentation outlines the diagnostic process and highlights "
"areas where the Linux kernelâ€™s diagnostic interfaces could be extended or "
"improved. By understanding the diagnostic flow, developers can better "
"prioritize future enhancements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:25
msgid "Step-by-Step Diagnostic Guide from Linux (General Ethernet)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:27
msgid ""
"This diagnostic guide covers common Ethernet troubleshooting scenarios, "
"focusing on **link stability and detection** across different Ethernet "
"environments, including **Single-Pair Ethernet (SPE)** and **Multi-Pair "
"Ethernet (MPE)**, as well as power delivery technologies like **PoDL** "
"(Power over Data Line) and **PoE** (Clause 33 PSE)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:33
msgid ""
"The guide is designed to help users diagnose physical layer (Layer 1) issues "
"on systems running **Linux kernel version 6.11 or newer**, utilizing "
"**ethtool version 6.10 or later** and **iproute2 version 6.4.0 or later**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:37
msgid ""
"In this guide, we assume that users may have **limited or no access to the "
"link partner** and will focus on diagnosing issues locally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:41
msgid "Diagnostic Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:43
msgid ""
"**Link is up and stable, but no data transfer**: If the link is stable but "
"there are issues with data transmission, refer to the **OSI Layer 2 "
"Troubleshooting Guide**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:47
msgid ""
"**Link is unstable**: Link resets, speed drops, or other fluctuations "
"indicate potential issues at the hardware or physical layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:50
msgid "**No link detected**: The interface is up, but no link is established."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:53
msgid "Verify Interface Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:55
msgid ""
"Begin by verifying the status of the Ethernet interface to check if it is "
"administratively up. Unlike `ethtool`, which provides information on the "
"link and PHY status, it does not show the **administrative state** of the "
"interface. To check this, you should use the `ip` command, which describes "
"the interface state within the angle brackets `\"<>\"` in its output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:61
msgid ""
"For example, in the output `<NO-CARRIER,BROADCAST,MULTICAST,UP>`, the "
"important keywords are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:64
msgid "**UP**: The interface is in the administrative \"UP\" state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:65
msgid ""
"**NO-CARRIER**: The interface is administratively up, but no physical link "
"is detected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:68
msgid ""
"If the output shows `<BROADCAST,MULTICAST>`, this indicates the interface is "
"in the administrative \"DOWN\" state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../networking/diagnostic/twisted_pair_layer1_diagnostics.rst:71
msgid "**Command:** `ip link show dev <interface>`"
msgstr ""

